And I share a number of
studies, some of which

00:31:47.720 --> 00:31:50.920
you may already know,
about extrinsic versus

00:31:50.920 --> 00:31:52.440
intrinsic motivators.

00:31:52.440 --> 00:31:54.610
Studies actually
show when they ask

00:31:54.610 --> 00:31:58.360
girls, for example, to tutor
another girl in the piano.

00:31:58.360 --> 00:32:01.400
And they're told, hey, you're
going to teach her the piano.

00:32:01.400 --> 00:32:02.970
It's going to feel great.

00:32:02.970 --> 00:32:04.490
And they do a great job.

00:32:04.490 --> 00:32:07.170
When they're told, you teach
her the piano for half an hour

00:32:07.170 --> 00:32:09.900
and then you get a ticket to
go to the movies for free,

00:32:09.900 --> 00:32:11.810
well, they get frustrated.

00:32:11.810 --> 00:32:13.760
They sort of lose faith.

00:32:13.760 --> 00:32:15.260
And then when the
half hour is over,

00:32:15.260 --> 00:32:17.170
they bolt, whether
they've learned it or not.

00:32:17.170 --> 00:32:20.500
The point is, extrinsic
motivators actually mentally

00:32:20.500 --> 00:32:22.390
block our intrinsic motivators.

00:32:22.390 --> 00:32:25.090
We can't see our original
reasons for doing them.

00:32:25.090 --> 00:32:27.340
You know why I started
writing 1,000 Awesome Things?

00:32:27.340 --> 00:32:28.470
To cheer myself up.

00:32:28.470 --> 00:32:30.490
I'll write 1,000 awesome things.

00:32:30.490 --> 00:32:31.370
That's cool.

00:32:31.370 --> 00:32:34.110
Then I started noticing
the blog counter.

00:32:34.110 --> 00:32:36.117
50 hits-- I'll
try to get 50,000.

00:32:36.117 --> 00:32:36.950
Well, that was easy.

00:32:36.950 --> 00:32:38.033
I'll try to get a million.

00:32:38.033 --> 00:32:40.180
I'll submit it to Fark
and Digg and Reddit.

00:32:40.180 --> 00:32:42.070
I'll just keep
cranking on this thing.

00:32:42.070 --> 00:32:43.750
Well, that's not monetized.

00:32:43.750 --> 00:32:44.900
I need to have a book.

00:32:44.900 --> 00:32:47.266
Oh, it's got to be a
bestseller, the 0.01%,

00:32:47.266 --> 00:32:48.390
otherwise it doesn't count.

00:32:48.390 --> 00:32:50.040
Oh, it's only been
bestseller for one week.

00:32:50.040 --> 00:32:51.810
You've got to get on the "New
York Times" bestseller list.

00:32:51.810 --> 00:32:53.240
Oh, it's got to be a
bestseller for 200 weeks,

00:32:53.240 --> 00:32:55.520
otherwise it's like, I'm not
going to make any money off it

00:32:55.520 --> 00:32:56.436
if it doesn't do that.

00:32:56.436 --> 00:32:58.860
I became obsessed.

00:32:58.860 --> 00:33:01.360
Drove myself into the ground,
sleeping three hours a night.

00:33:01.360 --> 00:33:02.750
I'm buying eye
makeup because I'm

00:33:02.750 --> 00:33:05.940
embarrassed to go to work
with black bags under my eyes.

00:33:05.940 --> 00:33:08.740
I lost my intrinsic
reasons for doing it,

00:33:08.740 --> 00:33:10.260
and I stopped writing.

00:33:10.260 --> 00:33:12.630
Because I was setting goals
and just achieving them,

00:33:12.630 --> 00:33:14.460
and they never ended.

00:33:14.460 --> 00:33:17.390
So we need to remember
to do it for us.

00:33:17.390 --> 00:33:20.520
Ralph Waldo Emerson
said, the hardest thing

00:33:20.520 --> 00:33:23.150
to do in the world
is to be yourself

00:33:23.150 --> 00:33:24.710
in a world that's
constantly trying

00:33:24.710 --> 00:33:26.130
to make you something else.

00:33:26.130 --> 00:33:29.300
I think I butchered the quote,
but it's pretty close to that.

00:33:29.300 --> 00:33:30.380
And that's the point.

00:33:30.380 --> 00:33:31.430
How do you do it for you?

00:33:31.430 --> 00:33:32.805
Especially when
everything you do

00:33:32.805 --> 00:33:35.430
has a performance evaluation
and a paycheck attached to it.

00:33:35.430 --> 00:33:37.290
You have to get away
from that somehow.

00:33:37.290 --> 00:33:39.040
You've got to find
your intrinsic reasons.

00:33:39.040 --> 00:33:40.340
You've got to write
those down, and you

00:33:40.340 --> 00:33:41.965
gotta make sure
everything you're doing

00:33:41.965 --> 00:33:44.990
is for those intrinsic reasons.

00:33:44.990 --> 00:33:47.250
Advice is always
going to conflict.

00:33:47.250 --> 00:33:51.050
You can't take what
other people say.

00:33:51.050 --> 00:33:52.690
The pen is mightier
than the sword.

00:33:52.690 --> 00:33:54.130
Actions speak louder than words.

00:33:54.130 --> 00:33:56.440
Every single cliche conflicts.

00:33:56.440 --> 00:33:58.862
Ultimately, you have
to listen to yourself

00:33:58.862 --> 00:34:00.320
and that's the
hardest thing to do.

00:34:00.320 --> 00:34:01.778
In the book on
secret number eight,

00:34:01.778 --> 00:34:04.490
I have three tests to find
your authentic self, tests

00:34:04.490 --> 00:34:07.350
that I perform on
myself every six months.

00:34:07.350 --> 00:34:08.697
How did I do on the lake?

00:34:08.697 --> 00:34:09.280
You know what?

00:34:09.280 --> 00:34:10.110
I did it.

00:34:10.110 --> 00:34:10.611
I did it.

00:34:10.611 --> 00:34:11.693
And you know what I found?

00:34:11.693 --> 00:34:12.909
I did it with a life jacket.

00:34:12.909 --> 00:34:15.217
Because when I jumped in
that lake, first of all,

00:34:15.217 --> 00:34:17.300
there was something that
there wasn't in the pool.

00:34:17.300 --> 00:34:18.699
It's called waves.

00:34:18.699 --> 00:34:21.400
I didn't account for
that in my training.

00:34:21.400 --> 00:34:23.560
So it was harder for
me to swim in the lake.

00:34:23.560 --> 00:34:26.480
There was wind in the lake
and a bit of a current almost.

00:34:26.480 --> 00:34:28.530
So I did it, with a
life jacket, which

00:34:28.530 --> 00:34:29.830
I couldn't have done before.

00:34:29.830 --> 00:34:31.730
And I felt very proud of it.

00:34:31.730 --> 00:34:33.889
Because then I
thought, I can do this.

00:34:33.889 --> 00:34:35.889
And then-- it was a
couple summers ago--

00:34:35.889 --> 00:34:37.129
I did it more than once.

00:34:37.129 --> 00:34:38.670
I jumped in the lake
and went around.

00:34:38.670 --> 00:34:42.360
It was just that mental barrier
was erased because I put action

00:34:42.360 --> 00:34:43.719
in front of motivation.

00:34:43.719 --> 00:34:45.190
It's the hardest thing to do.

00:34:45.190 --> 00:34:46.870
Thanks for asking.

00:34:46.870 --> 00:34:47.659
Yes?

00:34:47.659 --> 00:34:50.610
How do you set expectations
that are high enough

00:34:50.610 --> 00:34:52.699
that they're
difficult to achieve,

00:34:52.699 --> 00:34:54.989
but low enough that
they're achievable,

00:34:54.989 --> 00:34:57.570
and how does that fit into
your internal motivations?

00:34:57.570 --> 00:34:58.350
You know what?

00:34:58.350 --> 00:35:00.240
We're going to blow
ourselves up in society.

00:35:00.240 --> 00:35:00.890
We are.

00:35:00.890 --> 00:35:01.890
We've got a problem.

00:35:01.890 --> 00:35:04.987
We used to live in a culture
called the culture of enough.

00:35:04.987 --> 00:35:06.320
We probably don't remember that.

00:35:06.320 --> 00:35:07.778
It was before most
of us were born.

00:35:07.778 --> 00:35:11.270
It was the 250,000 years
of our species' history up

00:35:11.270 --> 00:35:12.474
until the early 1900s.

00:35:12.474 --> 00:35:13.890
It's called the
culture of enough.

00:35:13.890 --> 00:35:15.235
You need enough food to eat.

00:35:15.235 --> 00:35:17.570
You need enough of a
house to live under.

00:35:17.570 --> 00:35:18.350
You need enough.

00:35:18.350 --> 00:35:20.808
And then at the turn of the
century, three things happened.

00:35:20.808 --> 00:35:25.450
Number one, mass production made
fridges and washing machines

00:35:25.450 --> 00:35:28.440
and these things that
came into our houses that

00:35:28.440 --> 00:35:30.089
actually increased our time.

00:35:30.089 --> 00:35:32.130
Now we could want more,
because we could do more.

00:35:32.130 --> 00:35:32.710
We had more time.

00:35:32.710 --> 00:35:34.751
And the other interesting
invention that happened

00:35:34.751 --> 00:35:36.220
was radios.

00:35:36.220 --> 00:35:39.140
Radios were the first
time advertisements ever

00:35:39.140 --> 00:35:41.040
entered the home.

00:35:41.040 --> 00:35:44.220
So now we were trained
to desire more.

00:35:44.220 --> 00:35:47.580
Paul Mazur, Lehman Brothers,
1927 in the "Harvard Business

00:35:47.580 --> 00:35:51.110
Review" wrote, we must
move society from a needs

00:35:51.110 --> 00:35:52.170
to a wants culture.

00:35:55.250 --> 00:35:57.180
Today, we live in
the culture of more,

00:35:57.180 --> 00:35:59.050
from the old culture of enough.

00:35:59.050 --> 00:36:01.957
Pop Momand from San Diego
was one of the first people

00:36:01.957 --> 00:36:03.040
to put his finger on that.

00:36:03.040 --> 00:36:04.011
He moved to New York.

00:36:04.011 --> 00:36:06.510
He was a successful cartoonist,
moved to a rich neighborhood

00:36:06.510 --> 00:36:08.350
and thought, I'm
surrounded by people

00:36:08.350 --> 00:36:09.590
who all have more than me.

00:36:09.590 --> 00:36:11.046
So he started to
write a cartoon.

00:36:11.046 --> 00:36:12.420
He moved down to
Manhattan, which

00:36:12.420 --> 00:36:16.080
was a poorer area at the time,
and started a cartoon called,

00:36:16.080 --> 00:36:17.790
"Keeping Up with the Joneses."

00:36:17.790 --> 00:36:19.300
He made up that phrase.

00:36:19.300 --> 00:36:21.770
It was called "Keeping Up
with the Smiths" originally,

00:36:21.770 --> 00:36:24.190
but didn't roll very well.

00:36:24.190 --> 00:36:27.120
That cartoon published
syndication for over 20 years.

00:36:27.120 --> 00:36:30.340
In the book, I have the very
first comic of that cartoon.

00:36:30.340 --> 00:36:32.910
It's old enough that we were
able to put it in the book.

00:36:32.910 --> 00:36:36.640
And so in this culture we live
in, one of more, more, more,

00:36:36.640 --> 00:36:38.080
it's risky.

00:36:38.080 --> 00:36:39.150
It's risky.

00:36:39.150 --> 00:36:41.870
Goals and expectations are in
the context of a society that

00:36:41.870 --> 00:36:44.050
always wants more of us.

00:36:44.050 --> 00:36:45.260
Employers want more of us.

00:36:45.260 --> 00:36:46.676
Our relationships
want more of us.

00:36:46.676 --> 00:36:48.290
We want everything
to be perfect.

00:36:48.290 --> 00:36:50.070
My wife tells a
great story where

00:36:50.070 --> 00:36:52.240
she talked to her
great-grandmother

00:36:52.240 --> 00:36:54.650
when she was over
100 years old, just

00:36:54.650 --> 00:36:55.940
maybe a year before she died.

00:36:55.940 --> 00:36:57.930
And she said,
Great-grandma, how am I

00:36:57.930 --> 00:37:03.100
going to find a man who makes
enough money, is really funny,

00:37:03.100 --> 00:37:07.080
is good-looking, has a great
job, is really compassionate,

00:37:07.080 --> 00:37:08.600
and loves me?

00:37:08.600 --> 00:37:11.840
And the woman couldn't
stop laughing.

00:37:11.840 --> 00:37:14.780
She was like, that
doesn't exist.

00:37:14.780 --> 00:37:16.240
You find one or two.

00:37:16.240 --> 00:37:17.890
You look for the rest elsewhere.

00:37:17.890 --> 00:37:21.530
Today in society, we want
everything from everybody

00:37:21.530 --> 00:37:22.680
all the time.

00:37:22.680 --> 00:37:23.920
It's scary.

00:37:23.920 --> 00:37:24.960
It's scary.

00:37:24.960 --> 00:37:27.930
And so the solution I propose
is remembering three words.

00:37:27.930 --> 00:37:31.620
Those words are,
remember the lottery.

00:37:31.620 --> 00:37:33.240
Remember the lottery.

00:37:33.240 --> 00:37:35.270
Remember that we've already won.

00:37:35.270 --> 00:37:36.370
What do I mean by that?

00:37:36.370 --> 00:37:41.180
There are 7 billion
people in the world today.

00:37:41.180 --> 00:37:47.830
There are 115 billion people
who have ever lived, ever.

00:37:47.830 --> 00:37:50.730
That means by being
alive today, you

00:37:50.730 --> 00:37:52.000
have already won the lottery.

00:37:52.000 --> 00:37:55.330
One in 15 people are alive.

00:37:55.330 --> 00:37:58.020
14 out of every 15
people will never

00:37:58.020 --> 00:37:59.870
eat a bowl of
chocolate ice cream,

00:37:59.870 --> 00:38:02.406
kiss their kids goodnight,
see another sunset,

00:38:02.406 --> 00:38:03.780
or be in the
kitchen with a group

00:38:03.780 --> 00:38:07.590
of friends singing happy
birthday to them ever again.

00:38:07.590 --> 00:38:09.830
You already won the
lottery by being alive.

00:38:09.830 --> 00:38:12.890
And the United Nations
World Happiness Report's

00:38:12.890 --> 00:38:14.300
coming out March 20th.

00:38:14.300 --> 00:38:14.800
Guess what?

00:38:14.800 --> 00:38:16.425
This country's going
to be near the top

00:38:16.425 --> 00:38:17.750
again, as it is every year.

00:38:17.750 --> 00:38:19.166
So we're probably
most people that

00:38:19.166 --> 00:38:21.780
don't have the time or
availability to watch this

00:38:21.780 --> 00:38:23.424
or the people listening in.

00:38:23.424 --> 00:38:24.090
I'm from Canada.

00:38:24.090 --> 00:38:26.870
We're always in the top five,
us and our Scandinavian brothers

00:38:26.870 --> 00:38:28.040
and sisters.

00:38:28.040 --> 00:38:30.140
We already got it good.

00:38:30.140 --> 00:38:32.100
If you have a
post-secondary education,

00:38:32.100 --> 00:38:36.280
you're one of 7% in
the world who does.

00:38:36.280 --> 00:38:38.590
If you make more
than $5,000 a year,

00:38:38.590 --> 00:38:40.100
you're above the world average.

00:38:40.100 --> 00:38:43.970
If you make more than $50,000,
you're in the top 0.05%

00:38:43.970 --> 00:38:44.955
already.

00:38:44.955 --> 00:38:46.290
You know the 1%?

00:38:46.290 --> 00:38:47.590
It's all of us.

00:38:47.590 --> 00:38:51.790
Everyone-- North America,
you won the lottery.

00:38:51.790 --> 00:38:54.570
And if you need even more
motivation than that,

00:38:54.570 --> 00:38:57.410
Google the image "pale
blue dot" and see the Earth

00:38:57.410 --> 00:39:00.760
from a distance, in the vast
expanse of the universe.

00:39:00.760 --> 00:39:05.550
And remember this is the only
place you could ever be alive.

00:39:05.550 --> 00:39:09.250
We got to be here at the perfect
time, in the perfect place,

00:39:09.250 --> 00:39:11.870
with the perfect amount
of oxygen and water,

